                        if (window.benji.isReady) {
                            // if cjsUserConsented event happens more than once this will ignore them.

of the biggest benefits of a <a data-i13n="cpos:8;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718516&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Chase Sapphire Reserve;cpos:8;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link ">Chase Sapphire Reserve</a> card over the Preferred is the $300 annual travel credit you’ll get each anniversary year. Thanks to Chase’s flexible definition of travel, you can use this credit to cover everything from flights and hotels to taxis, parking, and more.</p><p>Other benefits include airport lounge access with Priority Pass Select, credit toward TSA PreCheck or Global Entry fees, and perks when you book hotels with the Luxury Hotel &amp; Resort Collection. You’ll also get credits, waived membership fees, boosted rewards, and more with partner brands like Instacart, DoorDash, Lyft, and Peloton.</p><p>And like the Preferred Card, you’ll get boosted redemption value for booking travel through Chase with the Sapphire Reserve. But this card earns an extra 50%, or 1.5 cents per point. For example, if you have 100,000 points in your account, you could redeem them for up to $1,500 in value via Chase Travel.</p><hr><div class="credit-card card-module small-view"><div id="why-this-is-the-best-travel-credit-card-for-lower-cost-airline-rewards"><strong>Why this is the best </strong>travel<strong> c</strong>redit<strong> card for lower-cost airline rewards</strong></h3><p>The JetBlue Plus card beat out other airline cards with annual fees under $100 thanks to the added benefits it offers cardholders flying with the airline. We also chose this card thanks to the range that JetBlue flights cover. You may find similar deals from co-branded cards with more limited airlines (such as Hawaiian Airlines or Alaska Airlines), but we find the Plus card from JetBlue offers a solid amount of perks for a wider range of travelers.</p><p>In addition to rewards, you’ll get 10% of your points back when you use them to redeem a JetBlue flight, a $100 statement credit (one per year) when you book a JetBlue Vacations package, 5,000 bonus points each year, a free first checked bag, 50% off in-flight, and a faster path to Mosaic elite status with the airline.</p><hr><div class="credit-card card-module we compared with annual fees under $100, the Wyndham Rewards Earner Plus offered the greatest combination of rewards and added benefits to help ensure travelers who stay with the brand can maximize value.</p><p>According to the issuer, the 45,000-point bonus is worth as much as 6 free nights at participating hotels (though free nights may cost up to 30,000 points). Even after the welcome bonus, you’ll get up to one free night each year with 7,500 annual bonus points. Plus, the card offers a booking discount, automatic platinum-level member benefits, and more.</p><p>Wyndham Hotels themselves may be more common than you think, too. rewards</strong></h3><p>Despite its very steep annual fee, Hilton regulars can get a ton of extra value on their stays with the <a data-i13n="cpos:15;pos:1" href="https://global.americanexpress.com/card-benefits/view-all/hilton-aspire" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Hilton Aspire;cpos:15;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link ">Hilton Aspire</a> card.</p><p>Start with automatic Diamond Status with Hilton, for room upgrades (when available), bonus points, and more — plus up to $400 in resort credits ($200 semi-annually) for eligible purchases you make at Hilton Resorts. With qualifying Waldorf Astoria Hotels &amp; Resorts and Conrad Hotels &amp; Resorts properties, you can get another $100 on-property credit with eligible stays.</p><p>There are even plenty of benefits outside of Hilton. You’ll get up to $200 back per year ($50 per quarter) on flight purchases directly with airlines or through American Express Travel, up to $199 back each year for CLEAR Plus membership (with auto-renewal), elite status with National car rental service, access to concierge services, and more (terms apply; see <a data-i13n="cpos:16;pos:1" href="https://www.americanexpress.com/us/credit-cards/card-application/apply/prospect/terms/hilton-honors-aspire-credit-card/25330-10-0#FeeTable" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:rates and fees;cpos:16;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link ">rates and fees</a>).</p><p><em>All information about the Aspire card has been collected independently by Yahoo Finance. The Aspire card is no longer available through Yahoo Finance.</em></p><hr><hr><h2 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="more-top-travel-credit-cards-to-consider"><strong>More top travel credit cards to consider</strong></h2><p>The above cards may be the best according to our ranking system, but travel credit cards can be incredibly individualized depending on where and how often you travel, your budget, regular spending, and more. yahoo-link"><strong>Aer Lingus Visa Signature® Card review</strong>:</a> Earn a lucrative welcome bonus and companion ticket</p></li></ul><hr><hr><h2 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="how-do-travel-credit-cards-work">How do travel credit cards work?</h2><p>Travel credit cards earn rewards for making eligible purchases. You can use these rewards on travel-related redemptions, such as flights, hotel stays, and car rentals.</p><p>Many travel cards also provide travel benefits and perks, which could include airport lounge access, annual travel or airline credit, and elite status with an airline or hotel loyalty program.</p><div class="caas-pull-quote-wrapper caas-img caas-lazy" data-src><blockquote class="caas-blockquote"><p><a data-i13n="cpos:24;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/how-do-travel-credit-cards-work-172432075.html" data-ylk="slk:Learn more about how travel credit cards work;cpos:24;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>Learn more about how travel credit cards work</strong></a></p></blockquote></div><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="is-a-travel-card-worth-it">Is a travel card worth it?</h3><p>Travel credit cards are worth it if you get enough value from the card’s benefits and rewards to outweigh any potential costs, such as an annual fee. They might not be worth it if you don’t travel enough to take advantage of card benefits and rewards.</p><p>However, you don’t have to be a frequent traveler to use a travel credit card. Traveling enough for a card to be worth it for you could mean traveling once or twice a year, maybe less.</p><div class="caas-pull-quote-wrapper caas-img caas-lazy" data-src><blockquote class="caas-blockquote"><p><a data-i13n="cpos:25;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/are-travel-credit-cards-worth-it-194818494.html" data-ylk="slk:See if travel credit cards are worth it for you;cpos:25;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>See if travel credit cards are worth it for you</strong></a></p></blockquote></div><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="types-of-travel-credit-cards"><strong>Types of travel credit cards</strong></h3><p>When you’re comparing travel credit cards, it can be useful to separate them into two distinct types: general travel rewards cards and co-branded airline and <a data-i13n="cpos:26;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/best-hotel-credit-card-195543129.html" data-ylk="slk:hotel credit cards;cpos:26;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link">hotel credit cards</a>.</p><p>Think about your specific travel preferences to decide which type is best for you:</p><p><strong>General travel rewards cards</strong></p><p>With a general travel credit card, you’ll earn points or miles on eligible purchases, which you can put toward a number of flexible redemption options. General travel credit cards include cards like the following:</p><ul class="caas-list caas-list-bullet"><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:27;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718510&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Chase Sapphire Preferred Card;cpos:27;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>Chase Sapphire Preferred Card</strong></a></p></li><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:28;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718229&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card;cpos:28;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card</strong></a></p></li><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:29;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/american-express-gold-card-235212667.html" data-ylk="slk:American Express Gold Card</strong></a></p></li></ul><div class="credit-card mini"><a class="link rapid-with-clickid" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26722397&amp;s1=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34%04tdjuUEP7RuQG6MkCLhkurg%04yahoo_personal_finance_397" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" target="_blank" data-ylk="subsec:credit-card;elm:affiliate_link;elmt:red_ventures;itc:0;tar:oc.brcclx.com;tar_uri:/t;sellerN:Bankrate Credit Cards;ll3:product-available;pid:red_ventures_6375;pdid:American Express® apply</span></div></div><div class="btn-container"><a class="link rapid-noclick-resp cta" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26722397&amp;s1=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34%04tdjuUEP7RuQG6MkCLhkurg%04yahoo_personal_finance_397" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" target="_blank" data-ylk="subsec:credit-card;elm:affiliate_link;elmt:red_ventures;itc:0;tar:oc.brcclx.com;tar_uri:/t;sellerN:Bankrate Credit Cards;ll3:product-available;pid:red_ventures_6375;pdid:American Express® Gold Card;cpos:11;sec:mini-product;pkgt:horizontal-cta;slk:Learn more;pos:5">Learn more</a></div></div></div><p>Many of these travel card issuers have their own travel portals, like Chase Travel or American Express Membership Rewards. You can use these to book flights, hotels, rental cars, and more. They may also have a number of travel partners, to which you can directly transfer points or miles. For example, American Express Membership Rewards points transfer to Delta SkyMiles at a rate of 1:1.</p><p>The flexibility of general travel cards means you can travel with any number of different airlines or hotel brands and get the best bang for your buck. Each time you’re ready to book, simply shop around between the portal or partners and compare the best options for your specific travel plans.</p><p>These credit cards also allow other redemption options, such as statement credits, gift cards, and cash back. But you’ll generally get the best value by redeeming points or miles for travel.</p><p><strong>Airline and hotel credit cards</strong></p><p>Airline and hotel credit cards are typically co-branded between the card issuer and the airline or hotel chain. Here are a few examples:</p><ul class="caas-list caas-list-bullet"><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:30;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718522&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Southwest Rapid Rewards® Plus Credit Card;cpos:30;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>Southwest Rapid Rewards® Plus Credit Card</strong></a></p></li><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:31;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718532&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34%20Formula%20fields%20should%20be%20configured%20in%20the%20field%20menu%20dropdown" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:United Club℠ Infinite Card;cpos:31;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>United Club℠ Infinite Card</strong></a></p></li><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:32;pos:1" href="https://creditcards.chase.com/travel-credit-cards/marriott-bonvoy/boundless" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Marriott Bonvoy Boundless® Credit Card;cpos:32;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>Marriott Bonvoy Boundless® Credit Card</strong></a></p></li><li><p><a data-i13n="cpos:33;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26722373&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Hilton Honors American Express Card;cpos:33;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><strong>Hilton Honors American Express Card</strong></a></p></li></ul><p>These cards are best suited for travelers who prefer to fly with a specific airline or stay at a certain hotel chain. Maybe you live near a hub airport, frequent a destination where a specific airline offers the most direct flight options, or you enjoy the perks of a specific hotel’s loyalty program.</p><p>Instead of flexible rewards points or miles, you’ll earn points or miles within the airline or hotel rewards program, like Marriott Bonvoy points or American Airlines AAdvantage miles — and get a boosted rewards rate when you spend directly with the airline or hotel. These cards often offer a faster path to elite status tiers within these programs.</p><p>The added benefits of co-branded cards are designed to appeal to loyal airline or hotel customers. For example, your airline card may get you priority boarding, upgrades, free checked bags, and in-flight discounts. And your hotel card may offer early check-in or late checkout, annual free night awards, and on-site credits.</p><p>Co-branded travel cards aren’t for everyone, but they can add a lot to your travel experience if you have a strong airline or hotel preference.</p><p><a data-i13n="cpos:34;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/best-hotel-credit-card-195543129.html" data-ylk="slk:Check out our complete list of the best hotel credit cards;cpos:34;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>Check out our complete list of the best hotel credit cards</strong></a></p><hr><hr><h2 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="how-to-choose-the-best-travel-credit-card"><strong>How to choose the best travel credit card</strong></h2><p>Here are a few key details to look for in any new travel credit card:</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="1-annual-fee"><strong>1. Annual fee</strong></h3><p>No matter your budget, there’s a travel credit card with an annual fee that fits. You can find solid no annual fee options, like the Discover it® Miles general travel card or Hilton Honors American Express co-branded card. But there’s also The Platinum Card from American Express, which may set you back $695 per year (see<a data-i13n="cpos:35;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26256804" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:rates and fees;cpos:35;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "> rates and fees</a>) but comes with an abundance of valuable benefits and perks that can potentially give you even more value back each year.</p><p>The most important thing to keep in mind when deciding whether an annual fee is worth it for you is whether you can get enough out of the rewards and benefits to outweigh the cost — without spending more than you otherwise would or can afford.</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="2-sign-up-bonus"><strong>2. Sign-up bonus</strong></h3><p>For new cardholders, a sign-up bonus can offer major first-year value. These bonuses may be worth anything from 10,000 to 100,000 bonus points or miles — which can translate to hundreds of dollars in rewards value.</p><p>However, you should compare the terms of the bonus to your own budget before you apply. For example, you may need to spend $4,000 within the first three months of opening your card before you can earn the 60,000 bonus points. If that’s not within your typical spending, be careful not to take on debt to meet the spending threshold. Accruing high interest on balances can quickly outpace even the best bonus.</p><p>One smart strategy is opening a new travel credit card when you’re booking a trip you’ve been saving for. You may already be prepared to spend more than usual, which can help you reach the bonus requirement faster. Plus, you can earn rewards on those travel purchases to put toward future trips.</p><p><strong>Read more: </strong><a data-i13n="cpos:36;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/best-credit-card-sign-up-bonus-212458984.html" data-ylk="slk:See our picks for the best credit card sign-up bonuses;cpos:36;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>See our picks for the best credit card sign-up bonuses</strong></a></p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="3-rewards"><strong>3. Rewards</strong></h3><p>Rewards are one of the biggest reasons for many people to open a travel credit card.</p><p>Earning rewards with travel cards often works in one of two ways. You’ll either earn rewards on your everyday spending (groceries, gas stations, restaurants) to redeem toward future travel, or earn rewards on your travel spending to put toward future travel.</p><p>Some cards offer a combination of these rewards, but knowing which type of spender you are can be useful. If your monthly budget is largely dedicated to everyday spending, you may get more value from the former. But if you travel frequently and spend a lot of money on flights, hotels, and rental cars, you can quickly rack up more points with travel-based rewards categories.</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="4-travel-perks-and-benefits"><strong>4. Travel perks and benefits</strong></h3><p>Many travel rewards credit cards — especially the most premium cards with high annual fees — really shine when it comes to added perks and benefits. These benefits can help you offset the annual fee and save money each time you travel.</p><p>Take the $395 annual fee<a data-i13n="cpos:37;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718229&amp;tid=6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card;cpos:37;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "> Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card</a>, for example. Each year, you’ll get a $300 annual credit for bookings through Capital One Travel and 10,000 bonus miles (equal to $100 towards travel) on your account anniversary. Already, that’s enough to wipe out the annual cost — before accounting for any rewards and other benefits (like up to $100 in fee credits toward<a data-i13n="cpos:38;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/how-to-get-tsa-precheck-for-free-with-a-credit-card-205021447.html" data-ylk="slk:TSA PreCheck;cpos:38;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"> TSA PreCheck</a> or Global Entry and Priority Pass Select airport lounge membership).</p><p>Just remember: Choose a card with benefits that help you save on purchases you would still have made otherwise. If you tend to arrive shortly before takeoff and don’t care about airport lounge access, you won’t actually get the $200 potential value from that benefit.</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="5-travel-insurance-and-protections"><strong>5. Travel insurance and protections</strong></h3><p>One unique aspect of travel credit cards is the protections you can get as a cardholder when you travel. Common protections offered by travel credit cards include trip cancellation and interruption insurance, car rental insurance, trip delay reimbursement, baggage delay insurance, access to emergency assistance services, and more.</p><p>As long as you pay for your travel expenses with the card (booking flights, hotels, tours, etc.) you can qualify for these travel protection benefits. Like any coverage, though, you should make sure to read the fine print of what your individual card offers. These benefits can vary greatly between different travel cards, so make sure to look for details in your card agreement.</p><div class="o-safeframe" data-src="bankrate-personal-finance" data-contentid="bfb57335-7d38-4a74-bf4b-b34e0a04cff0" data-subid="6f91b6e0-8bf3-4996-acaa-9dd1cd504a34&#x4;tdjuUEP7RuQG6MkCLhkurg&#x4;yahoo_personal_finance_397 finance-US-en-US-def" data-utmcampaign="yahoo-finance-cardmatch" data-resizer="true" style="height:0;width:100%;overflow:hidden;padding:0 1px 5px"></div><p><strong>More travel credit card tips</strong></p><ul holidays? 5 reasons to open a new travel card now;cpos:43;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link">Traveling for the holidays? 5 reasons to open a new travel card now</a></p></li></ul><hr><h2 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="travel-credit-cards-frequently-asked-questions-faqs"><strong>Travel credit cards frequently asked questions (FAQs)</strong></h2><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="should-i-get-a-travel-credit-card"><strong>Should I get a travel credit card?</strong></h3><p>Travel rewards credit cards can make a great addition to your wallet, even if you only travel a few times per year. Be sure to compare different travel card options to find the combination of annual fee, rewards, benefits, and sign-up bonus that works best for your travel plans and spending.</p><p>There may be a few reasons why a travel credit card isn’t right for you, though:</p><ul class="caas-list caas-list-bullet"><li><p><strong>You’re already in credit card debt.</strong> Avoid adding another card — especially one with a potentially high annual fee — to your wallet if you already have high-interest debt. Eliminating those balances will help you save a lot more in interest than any value travel rewards could offer.</p></li><li><p><strong>You don’t want to keep up with a rewards strategy.</strong> Travel credit cards can be most lucrative if you maximize how you earn and redeem rewards. If you don’t want to spend the time strategizing bonus categories and the best redemption options, a credit card with a simpler rewards structure may be better for you.</p></li><li><p><strong>You don’t have great credit.</strong> Travel credit cards generally require a good-to-excellent credit score to qualify for approval. If your credit isn’t in a great place right now, focus on<a data-i13n="cpos:44;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/how-to-increase-credit-score-with-credit-card-201034337.html" data-ylk="slk:improving your score;cpos:44;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"> improving your score</a> before you apply for a new card.</p></li></ul><p>If you are ready to open a travel credit card, time your application wisely. The spending thresholds to earn your welcome bonus can be high, so you may want to plan your application around your next trip. The money you’ve already saved can help you score the bonus when you book your travel, and you’ll also earn bonus points or miles for your next trip.</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="which-credit-card-is-best-for-travel"><strong>Which credit card is best for travel?</strong></h3><p>If you're new to travel credit cards, the<a data-i13n="cpos:45;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718230&amp;tid=96c9a7f8-3f9b-402a-bfab-a80419db35b0" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Capital One Venture Rewards card;cpos:45;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "> <strong>Capital One Venture Rewards card</strong></a> is a great place to start — you can earn 2x miles on everything, and it's easy to redeem your miles through Capital One's travel portal.</p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="which-card-is-better-for-international-travel"><strong>Which card is better for international travel?</strong></h3><p>When traveling abroad, look for credit cards that don't charge foreign transaction fees. One of our top picks for<a data-i13n="cpos:46;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/best-credit-cards-no-foreign-transaction-fees-234302581.html" data-ylk="slk:cards that don't charge a foreign transaction fee;cpos:46;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"> cards that don't charge a foreign transaction fee</a> is the<a data-i13n="cpos:47;pos:1" href="https://oc.brcclx.com/t?lid=26718234" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank" data-ylk="slk:Capital One SavorOne Cash Rewards Credit Card;cpos:47;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "> <strong>Capital One SavorOne Cash Rewards Credit Card</strong></a>.</p><p><strong>Related: </strong><a data-i13n="cpos:48;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/use-credit-card-for-international-travel-215322356.html" data-ylk="slk:How to use your credit card for international travel;cpos:48;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>How to use your credit card for international travel</strong></a></p><h3 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="which-travel-credit-card-is-most-elite"><strong>Which travel credit card is most elite?</strong></h3><p>For a premium travel experience, the Capital One Venture X Rewards is our top pick.</p><div class="caas-pull-quote-wrapper caas-img caas-lazy" data-src><blockquote class="caas-blockquote"><p><a data-i13n="cpos:50;pos:1" href="https://finance.yahoo.com/personal-finance/capital-one-venture-x-review-225141240.html" data-ylk="slk:Read our full review of the Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card;cpos:50;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas;outcm:mb_qualified_link;_E:mb_qualified_link;ct:story;" class="link  yahoo-link"><strong>Read our full review of the Capital One Venture X Rewards Credit Card</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p></blockquote></div><hr><h2 class="caas-jump-link-heading" id="our-methodology"><strong>Our methodology</strong></h2><p>To begin our search for the best travel credit cards, we evaluated more than 70 credit cards currently available from major issuers. Each of these cards is marketed as a travel card and earns rewards in the form of points or miles.</p><p>Our scoring system involves evaluating each card based on a number of details we believe are important to cardholders looking for travel rewards credit cards. We begin with some general credit card details that we look for across every card type, such as annual fee, APR, welcome offer, card security, issuer transparency, and more. Specifically for travel credit cards, we also looked at factors like rewards, redemption options, welcome offer, and added benefits and perks.</p><p>Once each card was given a score, we again evaluated the highest-scoring overall cards for the superlatives included on our list (best no annual fee travel card, best premium travel card, etc.).</p><p>We filtered criteria for individual superlatives to find the best card among our already high-scoring options. For example, our pick for the best beginner travel card was chosen for its high score while excluding any co-branded airline or hotel cards and any cards with annual fees over $100. We believe beginner travel card users often look for simple cards that can help them maximize rewards without a high cost or needing to strategize — and we wanted our top options to reflect that.</p><p>We used a similar strategy for our co-branded card picks, too. We understand that any airline and hotel credit cards will be highly subjective depending on any users’ preferred travel brands. That being said, the cards that made our list are the highest-scoring cards based on our overall travel card criteria and from wide-reaching travel brands. If an airline, for example, did not have ample coverage throughout the United States, we gave preference to a co-branded card with a broader range of service.</p><p>While we strive to keep our rankings objective, we also know that different cards may be better suited for different types of travelers, budgets, spending habits, and more. Before you apply for any new card, make sure you compare multiple options from different issuers to decide the best combination of fees, rewards, benefits, and overall value that works for you.</p><p><em>This article was edited by </em><a data-i13n="cpos:51;pos:1" href="https://www.yahoo.com/author/rebecca-mccracken/" data-ylk="slk:Rebecca McCracken;cpos:51;pos:1;elm:context_link;itc:0;sec:content-canvas" class="link "><em>Rebecca McCracken</em></a></p><hr><p><em>Editorial Disclosure: The information in this article has not been reviewed or approved by any advertiser. All opinions belong solely to Yahoo Finance and are not those of any other entity. The details on financial products, including card rates and fees, are accurate as of the publish date. All products or services are presented without warranty. Check the bank’s website for the most current information. This site doesn't include all currently available offers. Credit score alone does not guarantee or imply approval for any financial product.</em></p><div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></article></div></div><script type="text/javascript">

var ubDetection = function() {
    // primary check: create node has sensitive id on the fly
    const decoyId = 'my-ads';
    const decoyNode = document.createElement('div');
    decoyNode.setAttribute('id', decoyId);
    decoyNode.innerHTML = decoyId;
    document.body.appendChild(decoyNode);
    
    const decoyNodeIns = document.querySelector(`#${decoyId}`);
    if (decoyNodeIns && decoyNodeIns.offsetHeight === 0) {
        decoyNodeIns.remove();
        return true;
    }
    decoyNodeIns.remove();
    
    // additional check: check all necessary ad pos dimension
    if (shouldCheckPosition) {
        const { positions } = dabConfig;
        let adposNodeCount = 0;
        let hidenPosNodeCount = 0;
        
        for (const position of positions) {
            const adposNode = document.querySelector(`#${position}`);
            if (adposNode) {
                adposNodeCount += 1;
                if (adposNode.offsetHeight === 0) {
                    hidenPosNodeCount += 1;
                }
            }
        }

        if (adposNodeCount > 0 && adposNodeCount === hidenPosNodeCount) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}

var initABDetection = function() {
    var daTrk = '0';
    var cExpiry = 0;
    var expires = new Date();

    /* General AB Check */
    var abSelector = document.getElementById('advertisement-thamba');
    if (!abSelector) {
        daTrk = '1';
        cExpiry = cookieDuration;
    }

    /* Specific AB Check */
    if (dabConfig.enableUBDetection) {
        const isUBActive = ubDetection();
        if (isUBActive) {
            daTrk = '1';
            cExpiry = cookieDuration;
        }
    }

    expires.setMinutes(expires.getMinutes() + cExpiry);

    // Sets cookie if we have to clear (block -> non-blocked state) OR
    // set with value (non-block -> block state)
    if ((thamba && daTrk === '0') || (!thamba && daTrk === '1')) {
        w.wafer.utils.setCookie(cookieName, daTrk, {expires: expires, domain: location.hostname, path:'/'});
    }

    // if (dabConfig.enableABPDetection && daTrk === '1') { // will uncomment when we can detect container collapsed
    if (dabConfig.enableABPDetection) {
        detectABP(daTrk);
    }
};

w.wafer && w.wafer.utils && w.wafer.ready  && w.wafer.ready(function () {
    setTimeout(initABDetection, dabConfig.detectionTimeout || 300);
});
    }(window));
